description.narrative: Output 1.2 More children, adolescents and women benefit from improved and equitable use of high-impact maternal, new-born, child, and adolescent health interventions, which contributes to Health And Development In Early Childhood And Adolescence, Immunization Services As Part Of Primary Health Care, Mental Health And Psychosocial Well-Being, Nutrition Of Adolescents And Women, Strengthening Primary Health Care And High-Impact Health Interventions, Strengthening Primary Health Care And High-Impact Health Interventions (Covid). UNICEF aims to achieve this through Advocacy And Public Engagement, Developing And Leveraging Resources And Partnerships, Fostering Innovation And Use Of New Technologies, Systems Strengthening And Institution Building, Systems Strengthening To Leave No One Behind, United Nations Working Together. This contributes to the following Country Programme result: By 2022, more vulnerable neonates, infants and children survive and thrive and fewer women die during pregnancy and childbirth

description.narrative: Integrated health service delivery brings in the best value for money. More than half of UNICEF’s health investments are at the Primary Health Care level. Almost 2,000 PHC facilities and;23;CEmONC;hospitals supported to provide free MNH services reaching more than half a million PLWs; 322,066 PLW received ANC visits which is 35 percent of the national need.; During 2021, UNICEF reachedmarginalized 587,877 children and 133,653 Pregnant Lactating Women (PLWs) with four rounds of IOR. Lifesaving medicines, vaccines, and health supplies worth USD 20 million (20% of the budget) were procured and distributed to ensure continuity of services. | Status:On-track | As-of Date:16/01/2022
